{
  "texts": [
    "Now suppose for reductio that y ∈ cl(⇓X ′), so there is a u ⊑ y and a y ′ ∈ X ′ such that u ⊑ y ′.",
    "Then by Definition 5.52.4, there is a z ∈ S ′ such that z ⊑ u.",
    "Since z ⊑ u ⊑ y, z ⊑ u ⊑ y ′, z ∈ S ′, and y, y ′ ∈ S ′, we have z ⊑ ′ y and z ⊑ ′ y ′.",
    "By (i), z ⊑ ′ y implies z ̸ ∈ X ′, which with z ⊑ ′ y ′ and persistence for X ′ with respect to ⊑ ′ implies y ′ ̸ ∈ X ′, contradicting y ′ ∈ X ′ from above.",
    "Hence y ̸ ∈ cl(⇓X ′), which with y ⊑ ′ x implies x ̸ ∈ int(cl(⇓X ′)), so x ̸ ∈ X, which completes the proof of part 2.For part 3, the observations made in the proof of part 1 imply that the identity map on S ′ is a strong embedding from F ′ to F (Definition 3.2.12), so by Proposition 3.7.3, F ⊩ φ implies F ′ ⊩ φ.The following proposition shows that being a selective subframe is equivalent to being the image of a strict strong embedding as in Definition 3.2.Proposition 5.54 (Embeddings and Subframes)."
  ]
}